-- ADP, Club Med, EADS, GDF Suez, Stallergenes: French Equity Market Preview
-- Albertina Torsoli
-- 2010-07-19T04:00:00Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-19/adp-club-med-eads-gdf-suez-stallergenes-french-equity-market-preview.html

          
          
             The following is a list of companies
whose shares may have unusual price changes in Paris. Stock
symbols are in parentheses and share prices are from the
previous close.  
 France’s CAC 40 Index fell 81.66 points, or 2.3 percent, to
3,500.16 in Paris. The SBF 120 Index dropped 2.2 percent.  
 Aeroports de Paris  (ADP FP): The operator of the French
capital’s Roissy-Charles de Gaulle and Orly airports reported a
2.3 percent increase in traffic for the month of June compared
with a year earlier. The shares lost 1.7 percent to 53.60 euros.  
 Club Mediterranee SA  (CU FP) may be bought by BMB Group in
a transaction valuing the French travel company at about 800
million euros ($1.03 billion), the Sunday Times reported July
18, citing unidentified people familiar with the matter.  Thierry Orsoni , a spokesman for Club Med, declined to comment when
contacted by telephone. The shares jumped 4.3 percent to 14.28
euros.  
 European Aeronautic, Defence & Space Co.  (EAD FP): Airbus
SAS, the world’s largest aircraft maker, can double the 131
orders it received in the first half during the Farnborough Air
Show as global travel rebounds, Airbus Chief Operating Officer
 John Leahy  told reporters in London on July 17.  
 Louis Gallois , the chief executive officer of EADS, the
parent company of Airbus, said the same day he is confident of
winning a $35 billion U.S. Air Force refuelling-tanker order
pitting his company against a rival bid from Boeing Co. EADS
fell 0.8 percent to 16.42 euros.  
 GDF Suez SA  (GSZ FP): The operator of Europe’s largest
natural-gas network is planning a 6.4 billion-pound ($9.8
billion) cash offer for International Power Plc, the Mail on
Sunday reported, citing people familiar with the matter. Paul-
Alexis Bouquet, a spokesman for GDF Suez, declined to comment on
the report. The shares shed about 4 percent to 24.32 euros.  
 Safran SA  (SAF FP): Europe’s second-largest maker of
aircraft engines and General Electric Co., already partners on
narrow-body engines through the CFM International venture, said
July 17 they formed a venture to sell used parts and materials
to airlines that use CFM56 model aircraft. Safran lost 0.8
percent to 20.63 euros.  
      Stallergenes SA  (GENP FP): Europe’s second-largest maker of
allergy medicines could raise as much as 100 million euros in a
stock sale to help finance acquisitions if takeover
opportunities arise, Investir reported July 17, citing Chief
Executive Officer  Albert Saporta . The shares jumped 3.3 percent
to 56.80 euros.  
 Thermador Groupe SA  (THEP FP): The plumbing-supplies
wholesaler said second-quarter revenue climbed 7.9 percent to
48.3 million euros. The stock dropped 0.3 percent to 104.50
euros.  
